About 1890.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

In the older view, note at No. 8, the Chatham Club; the cabaret where Irving Berlin, the famous songwriter first started. Facing same is the old Chinese Theatre, that has now become the Chinatown Mission. This, in conjunction with the Arcade (wooden structure at the head of the bend) played a major role in the intermeicine strife that habitually flares up in this locality and thereby caused this turn to be known as the Bloody Angle. No. 3 has been stated as the site of the home of Anthony H. Doyer in 1809, the individual whose name is perpetuated here. Around the bend on the right, Scotchy Lavelle maintained a dive at No. 14. Occupying the Bowery corners were similar enterprises, Barney Flynn's and Callahan's.

Mott Street, north from, but not including Park Street, to, but not including Bayard Street.
About 1890.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

Doyers Street, north to Pell Street, showing a portion of New York's Chinatown. The photographers vantage point is the bend in Doyers Street, known as the "Bloody Angle". View 2 is a photostatic reproduction of the original.

About 1900
No's. 1-2

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

Mott Street, north side, east from a point in line of Park Street, to the Chatham Square (right), showing a portion of New York's Chinatown. At the left is the distinctive structure housing the Chinese Empire Reform Association and a Joss House. This is No. 20 Mott St. It also provided entrance to the enclosed passageway to Doyers Street, emerging at the "Bloody Angle". View 2 is a photostatic reproduction of the original.
